Movie: All the Beauty and the Bloodshed
Review: cried for the last thirty minutes of this one... one of those films that makes you feel an indescribable sense of loss and a never-ending admiration for those who came before, with a glimmer of hope that encourages you to turn pain and suffering into political action. to think that as late as 2010 one of David Wojnarowicz's videos ('A Fire in my Belly') was removed from a National Gallery exhibition due to it being accused as "offensive" to Catholic…

Watched this coincidentally while reading Camera Lucida again. The deadening stillness of the photographs, enlivened through the mechanisms of memory and film; The detail of the woman before the war, much like Barthes' mother, who pierces through the general interest of the image, marking herself as the only stable memory the man has in the post-war period. If to take a photograph is to get something out of your mind and make it an external object wherein we can more…
she was fearless, and crazier than him. she was his queen... and god help anyone who dared to disrespect his queen
